Heat a #saucepan{} on high heat (no oil!). Add the @lamb mince{200%g} and cook until browned, ~{5-6%minutes}. Use a #wooden spoon{} to break it up as it cooks. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the @red onion{1}. When the lamb has browned, drain off any excess oil, then add half the onion and cook until softened, ~{5-6%minutes}. Next, add the @ras-el-hanout{1%tsp} and half the @ground turmeric{1%tsp} and cook for ~{1%minute} more.

Add the @basmati rice{150%g} to the pan and stir to make sure it gets nicely coated in the spices. Then add the @water{300%ml}. Bring to the boil, add the @chicken stock powder{1} and stir to dissolve. Lower the heat to medium and pop a #lid{} on. Cook for ~{10%minutes} then remove the pan from the heat and set aside for another ~{10%minutes}. The rice will finish cooking in its own steam. This is your pilaf!

While your pilaf cooks, finish off your last few jobs. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}). Pick the mint leaves from their stalks and finely chop (discard the stalks) - @mint{1}(leaves picked and chopped). Halve the @lemon{1/2}. Drain the @lentils{1/2%cup} in a #colander{}, rinse under cold water and set aside.

Heat a splash of @oil{} in another #frying pan{} over medium heat. Add the remaining onion and cook until softened, ~{5%minutes}. Stir frequently to make sure they don't burn. Add the @baby spinach{125%g} and cook for ~{2%minutes} before adding the garlic. Cook until the spinach has wilted completely then stir in the lentils. Carry on cooking until the lentils are piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}. Season to taste with @salt{} and @pepper{} and set aside.

Put the @low fat natural yoghurt{99%g} in a #small bowl{} and mix in half the mint and a pinch of the remaining turmeric. Season with salt and pepper then set aside. When the pilaf is ready, fluff it up with a #fork{}, then carefully add the lentil mixture, remaining mint and a squeeze of lemon juice. Taste and add more salt, pepper or lemon juice if you fancy.

Serve the lamb pilaf in deep #bowls{} with a generous dollop of minty yoghurt. Enjoy!